4. Detailed Findings
4.1 Reconnaissance Activity (Port Scan)

Observation:

Multiple TCP SYN packets sent to various ports on the target system
No completion of TCP 3-way handshake

Wireshark Filter Used:

tcp.flags.syn == 1 && tcp.flags.ack == 0

Analysis:

This behavior is consistent with SYN scan techniques commonly used by attackers to identify open ports.

Conclusion:

Confirmed reconnaissance phase of an attack.
4.2 Brute Force Attack Detection

Observation (Splunk Logs):

Multiple failed login attempts (Event ID 4625)
Followed by a successful login (Event ID 4624)

Splunk Query:

index=windows_logs EventCode=4625 OR EventCode=4624
| stats count by EventCode, Account_Name, src_ip

Analysis:

High frequency of failed logins followed by success strongly indicates brute-force attack success.

Conclusion:

Account compromise likely occurred
4.3 DNS Beaconing Behavior (C2 Communication)

Observation:

Repeated DNS queries at regular intervals
Queries to dynamically generated/random-looking subdomains

Wireshark Filter:

dns

Analysis:

Periodic pattern suggests automated beaconing
Random subdomains indicate possible DGA-based malware

Conclusion:

Strong indicator of Command-and-Control (C2) communication
4.4 Suspicious HTTP Activity (Potential Data Exfiltration)

Observation:

HTTP POST request to external server
Unusual endpoint and data in payload

Wireshark Filter:

http.request.method == "POST"

Analysis:

POST requests used to transmit data externally
Destination not recognized as trusted service

Conclusion:

Possible data exfiltration attempt
